9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105052/asset/images/105052fig19a.jpeg" height="1116" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105052&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105052/asset/images/105052fig19b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1530" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105052&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105052/asset/images/105052fig19c.jpeg" height="930" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105052&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105052/asset/images/105052fig20.jpeg" height="1216" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Small bowel ischemia. Axial CT enterographic section obtained in the arterial phase shows an abnormal segment of small bowel with wall thickening and hypoenhancement (white arrows), findings indicative of ischemia due to thromboembolic occlusion (black arrow) of the superior mesenteric artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105052&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105052/asset/images/105052fig21.jpeg" height="1584" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Mesenteric lymphangioma. Axial CT enterographic section obtained for evaluation of Crohn disease depicts a nonenhancing mesenteric lesion (arrows) with attenuation similar to that of fluid, an incidental finding consistent with mesenteric lymphangioma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105052&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hara AK, Leighton JA, Heigh RI, et al. Crohn disease of the small bowel: preliminary comparison among CT enterography, capsule endoscopy, small-bowel follow-through, and ileoscopy. <em>Radiology</em> 2006;238(1):128–134.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2381050296">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16373764/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Crohn+disease+of+the+small+bowel%3A+preliminary+comparison+among+CT+enterography%2C+capsule+endoscopy%2C+small-bowel+follow-through%2C+and+ileoscopy&amp;author=AK+Hara&amp;author=JA+Leighton&amp;author=RI+Heigh&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Radiology&amp;pages=128-134&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiol.2381050296&amp;pmid=16373